### Static Members

Static members belong to the class itself, not to any specific object. All objects share the same static member.

---

### Static Data Members

```cpp
class Counter {
public:
  static int count;  // Declaration

  Counter() {
    count++;  // Incremented for each object created
  }
};

// Definition outside class (required)
int Counter::count = 0;
```

---

### Static Member Functions

```cpp
class MathUtils {
public:
  static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
  }

  static int multiply(int a, int b) {
    return a * b;
  }
};

// Called without object
int result = MathUtils::add(5, 3);
```

---

### Static Member Characteristics

| Property | Static Data Member | Static Function |
|----------|-------------------|----------------|
| Storage | One copy for all objects | Code section |
| Access | `ClassName::member` | `ClassName::func()` |
| `this` pointer | Not applicable | Cannot use `this` |
| Can access | Static members only | Static members only |

---

### Inline Static Variables (C++17)

```cpp
class Config {
public:
  static inline string appName = "MyApp";  // No separate definition needed
  static inline int version = 1;
};
```

---

> **Key Point:** Initialize static data members outside the class definition (or use `inline` in C++17). Static member functions can only access static members and cannot use the `this` pointer.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Car {
public:
  static int totalCars;
  string brand;

  Car(string b) : brand(b) {
    totalCars++;
  }

  static int getTotalCars() {
    return totalCars;
  }
};

int Car::totalCars = 0;

int main() {
  Car c1("Toyota");
  Car c2("Honda");
  Car c3("Ford");

  cout << "Total cars: " << Car::getTotalCars() << endl;
  return 0;
}
